   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1839_12_24_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>
                  <date when="1816-08-04"/>Dec<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> 24<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1839</dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BentR1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Sir</persName>
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>I am very much obliged to<lb/>
                    you for your present of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MurrJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                  <lb/>
                        Murrays</persName> travels, which I had<lb/>
                    read and liked and wished<lb/>
                    to possess - The book is very<lb/>
                    gentlemanlike both in style<lb/>
                    and feeling - and free from<lb/>
                    national prejudice, for or<lb/>
                    against - How very striking<lb/>
                    the contrast between <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MurrJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Murray</persName>
               <lb/>
                    past life in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#US">America</placeName> and<lb/>
                    present life at Court must be<lb/>
                    and what an amusing picture<lb/>
                    he could make of this - <hi rend="underline">if</hi> - <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>      Some of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MurrJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Murray's</persName> connections<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#KingM1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Harman King (formerly Miss Johnstone)</persName>
               <lb/>
                    now married to a son of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#KingR1">Lord <unclear>Lortons</unclear>
               </persName>
               <lb/>
                    and his sister <persName ref="./Personography.xml#JohnM1">Miss Johnstone</persName> live<lb/>
                    in our county of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Longford_IE">Longford</placeName>
               <lb/>
                    and in our neighbourhood<lb/>
                    and we have lately made their<lb/>
                    acquaintance &amp; found them<lb/>
                    very agreeable highly cultivated<lb/>
                    persons - They first put <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MurrJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Murrays</persName>
               <lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1839_12_24_page02.jpg"/>
                   
                   book into my hands and I<lb/>
                    was glad to be able to tell<lb/>
                    them without any flattery<lb/>
                    or authors compliments how<lb/>
                    sincerely I like it <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>   Can you tell me who is<lb/>
                    the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GoreC1">author</persName> of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Woman1">
                  <hi rend="underline">The Woman of[/underline]<lb/>
                        [underline]"the World</hi>
               </title>? - I see it is published<lb/>
                    by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ColbH1">Colburn</persName> - It must be written<lb/>
                    by some one perfectly well<lb/>
                    acquainted with the World<lb/>
                    at home and abroad - And<lb/>
                    born &amp; bred in <unclear>high</unclear> life - the<lb/>
                    manners are so well painted<lb/>
                    and yet without any of that<lb/>
                    ostentation of knowledge of<lb/>
                    fashionable life which <choice>
                  <orig>preten<lb/>
                        ders</orig>
                  <reg>
                     <hi rend="underline">pretenders</hi>
                  </reg>
               </choice> or those new to these<lb/>
                    things are apt to betray<lb/>
                    - And there is a spirit of<lb/>
                    virtuous indignation a fresh<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1839_12_24_page03.jpg"/>
                   
                   ness of mind in the whole quite<lb/>
                    wonderful &amp; admirable in<lb/>
                    one who must have seen<lb/>
                    &amp; lived with so many of<lb/>
                    the corrupt and heartless.<lb/>
                    - The book is full of Wit -<lb/>
                    most refined &amp; easy - &amp; various <lb/>
            </p>
            <p> Pray write a line to tell<lb/>
                    me the name of the author<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
                    I am <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BentR1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Sir</persName> Your obliged,<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p/>
            </postscript>
